< text>
My car died and I had to be towed home, 96 miles!! AAA told me it would be approx. 1.5 hours before a tow truck could get there. It was dark and getting cold. As I sat in my car feeling vulnerable and a little scared, I said to myself‚Ä¶ ‚ÄúI need a hero!‚Äù  Just a quick 20ish minutes later, Rodney from E&C Towing showed up!!  Rodney was polite, professional, and efficient as he hooked up my car. He was kind and thoughtful as he invited me to wait in the truck where it was warm and a true gentleman as he asked if I needed assistance getting in.  (It was a really BIG flatbed truck!)  I was surprised at how nice, comfortable and clean the truck was.  The long ride home was actually delightful as Rodney drove carefully and safely through the heavy traffic.  The conversation was polite, interesting and I felt like I was just taking a drive with a longtime friend.  Rodney turned a stressful and scary situation into a pleasant one.  If you are a woman alone and ever find yourself stuck and in need of a hero, call E&C Towing and ask for Rodney!< /text>

Here, the omelets tasted like eggy bread dumplings with very little veggies or other ingredients inside.  Bland.
Instead of a brown sauce, there was an entire different dish served on top.  Kind of like a Chicken Kung Pao with battered chicken chunks, water chestnuts, pea pods and carrots. < Review>
Awesome food. Very large dishes. Be prepared to take some home. Price was perfect. Fed 5 adults with 4 take home boxes (we divided the left overs equally into the cartoons to create full meals) all for under $80 + tip. We ordered 3 entrees (orange chicken, curry chicken, garlic shrimp)(a healthy amount of white rice is included), plus 2 sides (simple fried rice, so good and house chow mien, this is no ordinary chow mien, it has chicken, beef and shrimp, yes all 3 in 1). Granted there may be some nights we could finish more but we'd be stuffed to sickness. Also, its a very relaxed atmosphere, TV playing and diner type tables and chairs. And to top it off the food came out fast. Go for it. You'll love it.<//Review>

< Review>
Had a big urge for Chinese food, after finding our usual place Fannies Wok unexplicitly closed on a Sunday, we decided to go to Peony's after reading the good reviews. We were very disappointed. We knew we were in trouble when within 5 minutes of ordering our entire order appeared, soup, appetizer and main course. This might be a positive to some people, but to us it means they didn't prepare the food fresh. The portions are huge, but not appealing. The service was good, but when the tab was almost $70 for the three of us, we definitely won't be back.<//Review>

The cream cheese wontons changed my life. There, I said it. They're unbelievably good. I love them. My kids love them. My wife loves them. They're perfect. The edges are perfectly crisp, and the inside is wonderfully creamy.

Although the staff was very helpful, this hotel is in desperate need of an update. Beautiful views don't make a hotel experience wonderful if you can't enjoy the inside of the room. The room was very old and the heater did not work. Another hotel guest had to come in to fix it because there was no maintenance on the grounds that day - not very comforting during a pandemic. Although, as I said before, the manager was very helpful and accommodating, this is a sign that central heating should be installed. If it weren't for the great front line ocean view, I would not return to this hotel.< /Review>

< Review>
We had an oceanfront room. Beautiful view of the ocean across the street. Saw 3 whales spouting in the distance. The boardwalk walking trail was right there. Next door to Moonstone Grill and 5 min. walk to Sea Chest restaurant. Only 2 negatives for the room:  TV is not hi-def. and there is a step down from bathroom to the bed area. Very problematic for older people although we were well warned by management. We put a white towel on that area to remind us of the step and had no issues. Would stay there again.< /Review>

< review>
Small, super clean and steps away from the beach. The front office staff was friendly and helpful. Sure I guess the furniture could use an upgrade like some other review noted but the bathroom has been re done. I like a small hotel that I just pull in, park and check in.  I would definitely stay here again and I would try to get one of the front suites with a patio. There's a great coffee shop in town, Cambria Coffee. Otherwise I would bring some breakfast and lunch stuff. There are a bunch of good dinner places in town. And bring a chair or two for the beach. And don't miss the elephant seals or Hearst Castle when it re opens.</review>

<text>I want to say, I will be staying here again the next time I visit Cambria. With that said, there were some minor issues to out hotel room. Upon going into our hotel room ( we booked the partial ocean view) my wife said the bathroom smelled of urine. I will say it smelled a little funky to me, but not enough to make a complaint about it. What did warrant a complaint was that there were a couple of spiders in the top corner of the shower. But the front desk person came up quickly to take care of the issue. Our room came with a fireplace which we were looking forward to using. It did not work. We called again to the front desk and the front desk person did try to fix it, but ultimately could not. She offered couple different room options that did not have a view of the ocean; we opted to just stay in our room. She gave us a discount for the fireplace not working. We were in a rush checking out, and we left some items in our room. The front desk person called me hours later after check out to get my home address to mail it out to me; they paid for shipping. So, yes, there were some minor issues, but the view the room overall was clean and the value of the room with the view was great. <name>Sandra Essary<//name>< review>
Superior Ocean view room with a glass window corner.  My mom, who atte 89 can't get around much - watched & listened to it there all day. Otherwise, no complaints.  They offer (free) pastries and coffee in the lobby for breakfast and a 4 pm wine reception.

Beach area was interesting to walk on.

We went there at Christmas partly to see the Cambria Christmas Market light show. We loved it and the atmosphere in this little town so much that going to Cambria for Xmas is our newest tradition.

Moonlight restaurant next door... It really surprised me to find a chef with these skills in such a small town.  Very impressed.</review>

< text>
The hotel was nice enough - with a wine tasting and cheese event each evening, but do not be mislead by the photos on booking sites.Having paid an extra ¬£50 a night for a king ocean view, we expected a room similar to the ones displayed on the booking site. Instead, we got a room on the side of the building, overlooking a car park. The ocean is visible, but to see it, you have to go outside onto the balcony, which sits above the car park. (Dont dream of seeing the ocean from your bed, unless you are very lucky to get one of the rooms on the front of the building) - as far as I am concerned, we were given a partial ocean view room - and was therefore very annoyed at the 30% premium I paid for an ocean view room!Other than this, the rooms are nicely equipped and clean and the location is beautiful(although only 1 restaurant in walking distance) - I would recommend this hotel - buy only on a cheap deal - and never pay for the ocean view</text>

This lady came in to see our rehearsal facility and to get a feel on if she would be happy rehearsing at our place.    She wanted to look at all of the rooms, which is perfectly fine, however when we informed her that some of the rooms are being used by other musicians, and we could not interrupt their rehearsals, she became incensed.  She felt that we should break in on people who are paying to use the rehearsal room, just to satisfy her needs.  Then after showing her, the rooms that were available for her to see, she said that she wanted to test the room. If the last 30 years are an indicator, then we are located in an extremely safe area.  Lastly, just a random thought. Studios has been celebrating music, creativity, integrity, ethics of the highest degree, and a commitment to excellence in customer service, and in providing musicians with the highest quality equipment in a safe, clean, environment, with positive energy abounding.  I truly hope that this person can put herself in our shoes and understand that we don't always have time to set people up to test our rooms. < Response>
{'time': 1471327584504, 'text': 'To put it simply, our equipment is far from old.  Our P.A. Systems feature the latest and most technically advanced Mackie DL series,  digital mixers.  All of these were purchased new,  and installed in the last year.  Within the last 3 months, our 3 staged rooms have been upgraded, and now include brand new, state of the art, powered sub woofers.  All of our rooms have had brand new monitors installed, within the last 1 1/2 years.  Within the last year, we replaced all of our microphones with 45, brand new TC helicon Microphones, which are as good as any microphone out there.    Our drum sets are not only newer, but they are kept in spectacular condition.  Also, the cymbals we provide are pro level, and come at no extra charge.  We have worked hard, this last year, to install video cameras and video monitors, in our rooms, enabling our customers to film their rehearsals, at no extra charge.  Both the video cams and the monitors have been purchased new, and this is offered at no extra charge. The only "old" equipment that we provide is known as vintage equipment.  These are coveted and much more expensive guitar amplifiers, which are almost always preferred by professional guitarists. Most of our rooms have had new carpet installed, within the last couple of years.  When you walk into our lobby, the scent of fresh and free coffee tickles the nose.  I wish that I could respond to this review by saying I will work to improve these things, but the fact is that our equipment is state of the art.  Yes it\'s true, we do offer vintage guitar amps, but there is a big difference between old and vintage.   Nothing sounds sweeter then a vintage fender amp.'}<//Response>

<Pics>None<//Pics><resp>{'time': 1472275992744, 'text': 'To put it simply, our equipment is far from old. Our P.A. Systems feature the latest and most technically advanced Mackie DL series, digital mixers. All of these were purchased new, and installed in the last year. Within the last 3 months, our 3 staged rooms have been upgraded, and now include brand new, state of the art, powered sub woofers. All of our rooms have had brand new monitors installed, within the last 1 1/2 years. Within the last year, we replaced all of our microphones with 45, brand new TC helicon Microphones, which are as good as any microphone out there. Our drum sets are not only newer, but they are kept in spectacular condition. Also, the cymbals we provide are pro level, and come at no extra charge. We have worked hard, this last year, to install video cameras and video monitors, in our rooms, enabling our customers to film their rehearsals, at no extra charge. Both the video cams and the monitors have been purchased new, and this is offered at no extra charge. The only "old" equipment that we provide is known as vintage equipment. These are coveted and much more expensive guitar amplifiers, which are almost always preferred by professional guitarists. Most of our rooms have had new carpet installed, within the last couple of years. When you walk into our lobby, the scent of fresh and free coffee tickles the nose. This year's premium increased by 25% over last year.  If this continues, I won't be able to afford the policy when my dogs get older and really need it.

Also, they will not prequalify claims.  You have to pay upfront, and then they will decide if they are going to reimbuse you after you have already taken on the risk.  While they have been good at paying, it is a risk I have to take with every pet bill I authorize.

My suggestion:  Find another company.< /Text>

<Text>I am putting a two star review because I am very frustrated with how my claim process has been going.
In November my husband signed up for pet insurance. Our dog doesn't have any pre-existing condition. The policy went into effect on Jan 1, 2018. Our dog had a stomach obstruction/GI issue on Jan 6, 2018 which was a Saturday and our vets office was closed. We took him to an emergency room when he was showing signs that were troublesome. While at the ER they told us they needed to take x-rays and we immediately pulled up our policy to see if we would be covered. (as this can be a rather large expense). Upon review, we found that we should be covered and went ahead with the x-rays. The vet determined that our dog needed to stay overnight for monitoring, which was an additonal cost.
Once the ordeal was over, we submitted the claim. Two weeks later we received a message via the online portal (and in the mail a few days later) indicating that we needed to submit medical records. I submitted the records that same day (1/23/2018) and called the next day to confirm that Nationwide had received. They had. They told me it would be 30 days for them to review.
As we are approaching the 30 day mark (two days from now), I have wondered why this is an issue that is taking so long. If Nationwide isn't asking me for more information or calling my vet with questions, why would this take so long? So, I called to talk to a rep. The rep told me a few things: 1) Anytime a request comes in so close to the policy going into effect, Nationwide gets concerned that the policy is being abused. (WE SIGNED UP IN NOVEMBER WELL BEFORE KNOWING THIS WAS GOING TO HAPPEN) 2) Nationwide has sent a letter in the mail (not one via their online portal that they have used for every other communication), which I haven't received yet, telling me that as of 2/14/2018, they need another 30 days to review the medical records. (Why? I have no idea. Again, they are not asking ME for any other information, nor have they contacted my regular or ER vet in the almost 30 days they have already had) and 3) I was then told that all of my other claims that I have submitted since the first one are on hold until the medical records are reviewed. The other claims I submitted had nothing to do with the issue on Jan 6, yet I am having to wait on them to be resolved. I have received NO communication about that being something Nationwide would do.
I am just very frustrated with this process and it appears, through online reviews, that I am not the only one. I have asked to speak to managers and claim reviewers and have been told no. I would really like to know how to get some answers so that I can figure out what is taking so long.< /Text><Time>1519249140851</Time></record></dataset><record>

< review>
Take the money you would pay monthly for this insurance and put it in a savings account for your pet - you will be much better served (my vet suggested this when I first got the policy. I should have listened). I obtained this insurance for my dog when he was about a year and a half old. He did have a couple of pre-existing conditions for which I did not expect coverage (torn ACL in back leg and food allergies). I had this insurance for 3 1/2 years and Nationwide/VPI has declined both claims I have made for my dog's veterinary needs to one of the two pre-existing issues (yes, my dog is quite healthy and I have made only two claims). As a side note, when you want to dispute a claim, they make it incredibly hard and time consuming to do so.

Most recently, I received notification from Nationwide two months ago informing me that my payment option was expiring (credit card) and that if I did not update the information, my policy would lapse. I purposely did not update the information because I had decided I did not want the policy anymore (no payment was taken in April as expected.) Nationwide somehow found a way around the need for my updated information and began charging me again in May and June. I discovered the payments just after the June payment was deducted (the new charge had a 30% increase as well!) I immediately called them to find out how this happened and ask for a refund. The customer service representative simply said that they kept re-submitting the charge until the bank finally accepted it. I then explained that based on the information they sent me, I purposely did not update my information because I wanted the policy to lapse and I would like a refund. After a bunch of policy quoting and run around, I got no where except to have my policy cancelled as of today. If I want to attempt to receive a refund for the charges in May & June, I need to write a letter and provide supporting documentation to get it.

This organization has demonstrated to me at each turn that the only thing that matters is the almighty dollar and they are going to do everything they can to obtain and keep the money they received from their customers. I strongly recommend that you do not choose this provider.</review>

<Text>First visit here. Haven't had much experience with Persian food so I can't compare with other places but for the most part it was good. The Paneer Sabzi appetizer was not what I expected. There were no tomatoes or scallions like the menu advertised. I was surprised how long it took to get a dish that required no cooking. And overpriced at $5.99, but the Feta cheese was amazing. The Bademjoon stew was tasty and very comfort food. And the basmati rice with saffron was heavenly. The Chicken Kodeh wrap was good, but could've used a little more of the "sauce". The Olovieh sandwich was pretty much the same as the wrap except stuffed with potato salad. The saffron pistachio ice cream was yummy. Service was friendly, but again the food took awhile. Good thing we had time for a leisurely lunch. Will be returning to try dinner in the future.<//Text>< pics>

Wow! We passed by Grover Beach from Monterey and had lunch at this little gem.  Well priced and DELICIOUS food! The owner himself prepared our filet mignon, ground beef and chicken on a bed of  fluffy jasmine rice with grilled tomato/Anaheim pepper and a wonderful cucumber salad. We topped it off with hot and crispy falafel. My first experience with Persian food and I was not disappointed. The service was outstanding (given the current Covid restrictions) and super friendly staff. I highly recommend this great place!</Text>

<name>Leah Santa Cruz</name>< time>
1574323311683< /time>
<rate>4< /rate>< Text>
I had the Gheimeh Bademjan: the eggplant in it was very good and the flavor overall was nice, though I wish the split peas were a tiny bit softer. Partner got the lamb shank, which was perfectly seasoned and came right off the bone. The kabobs served here are decently sized, so even just having one would seem filling enough. Was kind of annoyed that a lot of dishes seemed to be unavailable, especially the Zoolbia Bamieh that I would have really loved to try. We got the saffron ice cream instead, which was still quite delicious and different. Our server was very sweet and attentive, though she seemed a bit nervous/anxious and quiet. Prices lean on the more expensive side, but having a Persian restaurant here is very nice and I'd like to try out more of the menu, so I'll definitely be coming back again.</Text>

<name>Carla Hurt< /name>< Date>
1553994524186</Date>
<Rating>1<//Rating>< text>
Attempts to deliver a cultural cuisine, of  poor quality, without a savory taste.
The Greek type salad almost tasteless arrived with canned cut olives on iceberg type lettuce with a few tiny pieces of welcomed Persian cukes and under ripe slices of tomato.  The eggplant appetizer came without a bread to spread it on, and it wasn't very tasty, bland. The main dish was a sweet chicken "stew ", more like a puree to eat with a plate of white rice. I've eaten better persian/turkish/Greek food elsewhere as to.state our palates know good Mediterranean/persosn food. Oh, the lentil soup was tasteless, how can a cook not.make it savory?  The attitude of the owner/manager was surprising too, as he was very negative about his business.
Maybe this was a bad day for the restaurant,  but I had eagerly awaited sampling the menu. If the owner/manager would welcome his customers as they arrive (we were the only ones there) and have explanations about the entress or a sampling plate, this would lend interest. I have travelled and lived all over the middle east, but have not experienced such a disinterested staff and blamd ess to the meal.< /text>
